name: Adam Zampa
analysis: The best white-ball spinner in the world? He takes wickets when nothing else is happening.

name: Cameron Green
analysis: Immense talent, but his back issues and high price tag make him a risky investment.

name: Cooper Connolly
analysis: A young talent for the future, but maybe a bit light for a heavy-duty squad right now.

name: Glenn Maxwell
analysis: The Big Show! On turning tracks, his off-spin becomes a genuine weapon alongside his bat.

name: Josh Hazlewood
analysis: Metronome! He lands the ball on a coin; boringly consistent and effective everywhere.

name: Josh Inglis
analysis: Innovative and modern; plays the sweep and reverse sweep beautifully against spin.

name: Marcus Stoinis
analysis: The Hulk! Muscles the ball over ropes and bowls heavy balls that stick in the pitch.

name: Matthew Kuhnemann
analysis: A decent left-arm spinner, but with Zampa/Maxwell there, he rarely gets a look in.

name: Matthew Short
analysis: Dominated the BBL but has struggled to replicate that form in international cricket.

name: Mitchell Marsh
analysis: The Bison is a beast with the bat, but if he isn't bowling, he is an expensive luxury.

name: Nathan Ellis
analysis: Skiddy bowler with a great back-of-the-hand slower ball; ideal for Asian conditions.

name: Pat Cummins
analysis: The Silencer! He knows how to win trophies; his cutters are deadly on slow pitches.

name: Tim David
analysis: Pure power who doesn't need sighters; risky on turners but deadly on flat decks.

name: Travis Head
analysis: He attacks in the Powerplay before the ball starts gripping; takes the pitch out of the equation!

name: Xavier Bartlett
analysis: Swing king from the BBL! A fantastic budget option for new ball wickets.

name: Litton Das
analysis: Looks like a million dollars, then throws it away; frustrating talent.

name: Mahedi Hasan
analysis: Utility cricketer; bowls flat off-spin and can swing the bat, average at both.

name: Mustafizur Rahman
analysis: "The Fizz"! On slow pitches, he is a king; cutters are his key weapon.

name: Nasum Ahmed
analysis: Powerplay dart master; bowls tight lines but rarely runs through a side.

name: Nurul Hasan
analysis: Brilliant keeper, arguably the best in BD, but batting is barely serviceable.

name: Parvez Hossain Emon
analysis: Young top-order batter; not consistent enough to warrant a bid.

name: Rishad Hossain
analysis: A tall leg-spinner from Bangladesh? Rare commodity and a wicket-taker!

name: Saif Hassan
analysis: Tried and tested, but hasn't succeeded at T20I level.

name: Shaif Uddin
analysis: Has been around for a while but pace has dropped; average all-rounder.

name: Shamim Hossain
analysis: Lefty finisher who has struggled to finish games effectively.

name: Shoriful Islam
analysis: Aggressive left-armer who swings it upfront; good for early wickets.

name: Tanzid Hasan
analysis: Young opener who attacks, but lacks the temperament for big innings.

name: Tanzim Sakib
analysis: Aggressive pacer, sometimes too much; prone to leaking runs.

name: Taskin Ahmed
analysis: Heart and pace! The best pacer Bangladesh has right now; genuine wicket-taker.

name: Tawhid Hridoy
analysis: Best young batter in Bangladesh; rotates strike well and plays spin smartly.

name: Ajayveer Hundal
analysis: Not auction ready.

name: Ansh Patel
analysis: Young spinner, too raw.

name: Dilon Heyliger
analysis: Can hit long ball, bowl medium pace; bits and pieces.

name: Dilpreet Bajwa
analysis: Hard-hitter, but inconsistent; pool is too deep.

name: Harsh Thaker
analysis: Steady but lacks explosive power.

name: Jaskarandeep Buttar
analysis: Backup pacer.

name: Kaleem Sana
analysis: Decent left-arm pacer; bench warmer here.

name: Kanwarpal Tathgur
analysis: Not enough exposure.

name: Navneet Dhaliwal
analysis: Good opener for Canada; bench option.

name: Nicholas Kirton
analysis: Lefty with class; impressive in World Cup. Worth a punt.

name: Ravinderpal Singh
analysis: Hitter but no consistency.

name: Saad Bin Zafar
analysis: Experienced; economical spinner but doesn't take many wickets.

name: Shivam Sharma
analysis: Spinner without variations.

name: Shreyas Movva
analysis: Average keeper-bat.

name: Yuvraj Samra
analysis: Domestic level player.

name: Adil Rashid
analysis: The Wizard! Slower through the air; he is England's biggest weapon in Asia.

name: Ben Duckett
analysis: Sweeps everything! Good against spin, but struggles against raw pace.

name: Harry Brook
analysis: Modern genius! Shots all around the ground; a pillar for your batting lineup.

name: Jacob Bethell
analysis: The next big thing! Dynamic talent and spin bowling all-rounder.

name: Jamie Overton
analysis: Fast bowling all-rounder who hits massive sixes; impact player.

name: Jofra Archer
analysis: Elite skill, fragile body; a high-risk investment but terrifying if fit.

name: Jos Buttler
analysis: Jos the Boss! IPL legend who knows these pitches better than most; essential pick.

name: Josh Tongue
analysis: Red-ball specialist; not suited for the T20 format.

name: Liam Dawson
analysis: The "Professor" of spin; highly skilled, restricts runs, and a smart pick.

name: Luke Wood
analysis: Left-arm pace is always in demand, but can be predictable; decent backup.

name: Phil Salt
analysis: Brutal against pace! If the pitch is flat, he wins the match in the first 6 overs.

name: Rehan Ahmed
analysis: Young leggie with swagger; a good option for turning tracks.

name: Sam Curran
analysis: Uses cutters well; good for sticky wickets and a clutch lower-order batter.

name: Tom Banton
analysis: Hockey shots on a cricket field; talented but inconsistent.

name: Will Jacks
analysis: Explosive bat and handy off-spin; a complete package for T20s.

name: Ali Hasan
analysis: Not threatening enough for top batters.

name: Anthony Mosca
analysis: Not auction material.

name: Benjamin Manenti
analysis: Sibling of Harry; doesn't offer enough with bat or ball.

name: Crishan Jorge
analysis: Needs more seasoning.

name: Gian Piero Meade
analysis: Just a squad filler; pass.

name: Grant Stewart
analysis: County pro (Kent); decent hitter, but not an international star.

name: Harry Manenti
analysis: Utility player, not a starter for a fantasy XI.

name: JJ Smuts
analysis: Solid domestic player (ex-SA); offers stability and spin, decent backup.

name: Jaspreet Singh
analysis: Average medium pacer.

name: Justin Mosca
analysis: Sibling duo, but neither makes the cut.

name: Marcus Campopiano
analysis: Club level stats don't translate to this level.

name: Syed Naqvi
analysis: Pass; too raw.

name: Thomas Draca
analysis: Not enough data to justify a spot in a competitive auction.

name: Wayne Madsen
analysis: County cricket legend, but entering his 40s; too old for a dynamic T20 squad.

name: Zain Ali
analysis: Too inexperienced for this stage.

name: Aarif Sheikh
analysis: Stabilizer, not a match winner.

name: Aasif Sheikh
analysis: A steady opener/keeper; decent backup but T20 demands more.

name: Basir Ahamad
analysis: Jack of all trades, master of none.

name: Dipendra Singh Airee
analysis: The "Tiger"! Gun fielder, handy bowler, and explosive finisher; cult hero.

name: Gulshan Jha
analysis: Very young talent; high potential as a hitter, but raw.

name: Karan KC
analysis: Known for lusty blows and wickets, but can be expensive.

name: Kushal Bhurtel
analysis: Aggressive opener who lives by the sword; hit or miss.

name: Lalit Rajbanshi
analysis: A tidy left-arm spinner on turning tracks; offers good control.

name: Lokesh Bam
analysis: Hitter but no technique.

name: Nandan Yadav
analysis: Doesn't have the pace.

name: Rohit Paudel
analysis: Young captain of Nepal; solid technique and anchors well, but struggles to accelerate.

name: Sandeep Lamichhane
analysis: Proven wicket-taker globally, but lack of recent top-tier game time is risky.

name: Sher Malla
analysis: Backup spinner; avoid.

name: Sompal Kami
analysis: Veteran all-rounder for Nepal; backup option at best.

name: Sundeep Jora
analysis: Not consistent enough.

name: Ashish Odedara
analysis: Too inexperienced.

name: Hammad Mirza
analysis: Not enough impact to warrant a slot in your team.

name: Hasnain Ali Shah
analysis: Standard medium pacer; no variety.

name: Jatinder Singh
analysis: Famous for his muscle-man celebration, but his batting is often slow and scratchy.

name: Jay Odedra
analysis: Part-timer quality; avoid.

name: Jiten Ramanandi
analysis: Bits and pieces, but not enough bits.

name: Karan Sonavale
analysis: Not good enough for this auction.

name: Mohammad Nadeem
analysis: A steady bowler and batter, but lacks the X-factor for fantasy points.

name: Nadeem Khan
analysis: Doesn't have the power game for modern T20s.

name: Shafiq Jan
analysis: Not ready for this level.

name: Shah Faisal
analysis: Average pace, no swing; easy to line up.

name: Shakeel Ahmad
analysis: Slow left-arm orthodox; only useful on a raging turner.

name: Sufyan Mehmood
analysis: Average seamer; doesn't threaten the stumps enough.

name: Vinayak Shukla
analysis: A domestic performer, but untested against the big boys.

name: Wasim Ali
analysis: Squad player only; doesn't offer enough value.

name: Abbas Afridi
analysis: A variation specialist with a good back-of-the-hand slower ball; useful on slow decks.

name: Abrar Ahmed
analysis: "Harry Potter" with the mystery spin! A massive asset on subcontinent pitches where batters struggle to pick him.

name: Azam Khan
analysis: Hits spin hard, but his fitness and struggle against high pace make him a liability.

name: Babar Azam
analysis: A classic run-machine; on tough, slow pitches, his stability is worth its weight in gold.

name: Fakhar Zaman
analysis: Fakhar-e-Pakistan! A high-risk, high-reward spin hitter; if he stays for 10 balls, he changes the game.

name: Haris Rauf
analysis: Fast as a bullet train, but sometimes travels the distance if he doesn't use his cutters properly.

name: Iftikhar Ahmed
analysis: "Chacha" brings experience and handy off-spin, but his power hitting has faded recently.

name: Imad Wasim
analysis: Very smart cricketer; his arm-balls in the powerplay are impossible to hit on turning tracks.

name: Mohammad Amir
analysis: Vintage class! He still has the angles and the cutters to fool batters in the death overs.

name: Mohammad Rizwan
analysis: The Energizer Bunny! He runs hard, sweeps everything, and guarantees you fantasy points every match.

name: Naseem Shah
analysis: Pace is pace, yaar! He has speed, swing, and a big heart to bowl the tough overs.

name: Saim Ayub
analysis: Stylish "no-look" shots are great, but he needs to look at the scoreboard and build an innings.

name: Shadab Khan
analysis: Currently out of form and bowling full tosses, but he bats well and is a gun fielder.

name: Shaheen Afridi
analysis: The Eagle strikes early! His first over swinging yorker is the most dangerous event in cricket.

name: Usman Khan
analysis: Knows UAE conditions inside out; he attacks from ball one but needs international consistency.

name: Charith Asalanka
analysis: A gritty middle-order player who plays spin well, but lacks the power hitting.

name: Dasun Shanaka
analysis: Captaincy kept him in the team, but batting has dipped; slower balls are still useful.

name: Dhananjaya de Silva
analysis: A classical player suited for Tests/ODIs; consumes too many balls in T20s.

name: Dunith Wellalage
analysis: Young talent with a calm head; left-arm spin is tidy but batting needs power.

name: Janith Liyanage
analysis: A seam-bowling all-rounder who hasn't quite cracked the T20 code yet; avoid.

name: Kamindu Mendis
analysis: Ambidextrous spin! He can bowl both off-spin and left-arm spin; made for these conditions.

name: Kusal Mendis
analysis: When he is hot, he sizzles; when he is cold, he freezes; frustratingly inconsistent.

name: Kusal Perera
analysis: Explosive lefty who plays like Jayasuriya on his day, but is made of glass (injury prone).

name: Maheesh Theekshana
analysis: Mystery spin in the powerplay? Yes please! In Asia, he is a nightmare to face early on.

name: Matheesha Pathirana
analysis: Baby Malinga! His slingy action is very hard to pick under lights in dew conditions.

name: Milan Rathnayake
analysis: A newer face with raw pace but lacks control; probably not worth a bid.

name: Niroshan Dickwella
analysis: He will play a scoop shot on the first ball and get out; entertains for 2 mins only.

name: Nuwan Thushara
analysis: Malinga 2.0! If you can't afford Pathirana, buy Thushara; deadly on low-bounce pitches.

name: Pathum Nissanka
analysis: The silent warrior! While others collapse, he scores crucial runs; very reliable.

name: Wanindu Hasaranga
analysis: 4 overs of gold in Asia! Plus he can pinch-hit; if the ball turns, he is unplayable.

name: Aayan Afzal Khan
analysis: Very young, smart left-arm spinner; good value.

name: Akash Tahir
analysis: Backup spinner.

name: Ali Naseer
analysis: Young all-rounder with potential; watch him.

name: Alishan Sharafu
analysis: Young talent; looks good but doesn't score big enough.

name: Aryan Lakra
analysis: Not enough impact.

name: Asif Khan
analysis: Power hitter; inconsistent in T20s despite ODI records.

name: Basil Hameed
analysis: Steady off-spinner; nothing flashy.

name: Junaid Siddique
analysis: Aggressive pacer; good yorkers but loses cool.

name: Karthik Meiyappan
analysis: Leggie; hat-trick hero vs SL, decent option.

name: Muhammad Jawadullah
analysis: Left-arm seamer; decent prospect.

name: Muhammad Waseem
analysis: Best Associate batter? Hits sixes for fun. Budget opener.

name: Rohan Mustafa
analysis: Veteran, past his best but experienced.

name: Sanchit Sharma
analysis: Average seamer.

name: Vriitya Aravind
analysis: Technically sound but too slow for T20; anchor.

name: Zahoor Khan
analysis: Slower balls are decent; decent backup.

name: Aaron Jones
analysis: "Jones the Giant"! He has immense power and hits huge sixes, but goes missing often.

name: Abhishek Paradkar
analysis: A young left-arm seamer; needs more exposure before he becomes a viable pick.

name: Ali Khan
analysis: The Yorker machine! Great for death overs, but needs to be accurate on slow pitches.

name: Andries Gous
analysis: A classy batter with South African roots; plays both pace and spin very well.

name: Harmeet Singh
analysis: Left-arm spin and lusty blows; knows Indian pitches well from his domestic days.

name: Jasdeep Singh
analysis: An honest trier who bowls medium pace, but lacks the quality for this level.

name: Juanoy Drysdale
analysis: Raw pace talent, but without experience, he is a liability in pressure situations.

name: Milind Kumar
analysis: Ranji veteran who brings stability, but plays T20s at a slightly slower ODI tempo.

name: Monank Patel
analysis: A solid anchor who captained USA to glory; safe pair of hands but limited power.

name: Nosthush Kenjige
analysis: A disciplined left-arm spinner who troubled big teams; gold on turning tracks.

name: Saurabh Netravalkar
analysis: The Oracle! An engineer who codes wickets; his left-arm swing is genuine quality.

name: Shayan Jahangir
analysis: Gets stuck at the crease too often; needs to improve his strike rotation.

name: Smit Patel
analysis: Former India U19 player, but hasn't had enough game time to justify a spot.

name: Utkarsh Srivastava
analysis: A developmental player; pass for now and save your budget for impact players.

name: Yasir Mohammad
analysis: A squad player; not enough data to suggest he can influence a match here.

name: Blessing Muzarabani
analysis: Tall, hits the deck hard, and difficult to score off; excellent budget pacer.

name: Bradley Evans
analysis: Can bowl decent pace and hit the ball, but a bits-and-pieces player at this level.

name: Brendan Taylor
analysis: Absolute legend, but retired; keep your paddle down unless it's a legends league.

name: Brian Bennett
analysis: A promising youngster, but lacks the experience to handle big match pressure yet.

name: Clive Madande
analysis: A finisher-keeper who has played crucial knocks, but technically limited vs high pace.

name: Dion Myers
analysis: A solid batter but doesn't have the strike rate required for this format.

name: Graeme Cremer
analysis: A legend for Zimbabwe, but he is effectively retired/coaching. Do not buy!

name: Richard Ngarava
analysis: A tall left-arm pacer who swings the new ball; offers great value for the price.

name: Ryan Burl
analysis: Can rip leg-spin and hit massive sixes, but he goes missing in many games.

name: Sikandar Raza
analysis: The spirit of Zimbabwe! Mystery spin, middle order power, and pure passion. Must buy.

name: Tadiwanashe Marumani
analysis: Has talent but hasn't converted it into runs; too risky for a main squad.

name: Tashinga Musekiwa
analysis: A finisher who can bowl, but unproven at the top level.

name: Tinotenda Maposa
analysis: A young seamer who needs more time in the domestic circuit; skip.

name: Tony Munyonga
analysis: A fringe player who hasn't made enough impact to warrant a slot.

name: Wellington Masakadza
analysis: Experienced left-arm spinner, but purely a defensive bowler; won't win matches.

name: Scott Edwards
analysis: Captain Courageous! He doesn't have a power game, but he sweeps everything‚Äîpace, spin, even the dust off the pitch. Good for stability, bad for strike rate.

name: Colin Ackermann
analysis: A solid county professional. He gives you stability with the bat and bowls handy off-spin, but he won't set the stadium on fire. A safe "Dal Chawal" pick.

name: Noah Croes
analysis: A young backup keeper. Unless your main keeper is injury-prone and you have $0.5 left, look elsewhere.

name: Bas de Leede
analysis: The One-Man Army! He bowls heavy pace at the death and bats in the top 4. Buying him is like buying two players for the price of one. Massive value!

name: Aryan Dutt
analysis: A tall off-spinner who dares to bowl in the powerplay. He doesn't turn it much, but his height and accuracy annoy batters into making mistakes.

name: Fred Klaassen
analysis: A decent left-arm pacer, but he lacks the X-factor to trouble top-tier international batters on flat tracks.

name: Kyle Klein
analysis: Very young and raw. He is a project for the future, not a weapon for your high-stakes auction war today.

name: Michael Levitt
analysis: A clean hitter of the cricket ball! He can surprise you with a quickfire 30 at the top, but he is still unproven against high-quality spin.

name: Zach Lion-Cachet
analysis: A developmental player. Save your virtual money for someone who is guaranteed to make the starting XI.

name: Max O'Dowd
analysis: The Anchor. He will stay at the crease, but sometimes he stays too long without scoring fast enough. Good for collapse prevention only.

name: Logan van Beek
analysis: The Super Over Hero! He brings incredible energy and can hit big sixes, but his bowling can be expensive if he misses his yorker.

name: Timm van der Gugten
analysis: An experienced campaigner, but his pace has dropped significantly. On a good batting track, he might become "run-machine" for the opposition.

name: Roelof van der Merwe
analysis: The Bulldog! He has more passion than skill at this age, but he fights for every inch on turning tracks. A good vibe player.

name: Paul van Meekeren
analysis: Fast and skiddy, but can be very erratic. He bowls one unplayable delivery followed by two wide balls. Frustrating to own.

name: Saqib Zulfiqar
analysis: A bits-and-pieces leg-spinner who doesn't offer enough impact with bat or ball to warrant a precious overseas slot.

name: Mitchell Santner
analysis: The Glasses-wearing Genius! He varies his pace so well that batters fall asleep and get out. Extremely economical.

name: Finn Allen
analysis: He hits the ball to the moon or returns to the pavilion in the first over. Frustrating, but if he clicks, you win in the powerplay.

name: Michael Bracewell
analysis: The Beast! He bowls tight off-spin and murders the ball in the death overs. Highly underrated asset.

name: Mark Chapman
analysis: A solid middle-order player who plays spin nicely. Flies under the radar, but gets the job done quietly.

name: Devon Conway
analysis: Mr. Consistent. He sweeps, he cuts, he anchors. The perfect bankable batter for subcontinent pitches.

name: Jacob Duffy
analysis: A domestic giant in NZ, but hasn't translated that to international dominance. Bench warmer.

name: Lockie Ferguson
analysis: Express pace! He is a Ferrari engine in a fragile body. If he plays, he takes wickets; if he doesn't, he takes up a slot.

name: Matt Henry
analysis: A new-ball wizard. If there is a hint of movement, he will find the edge. Reliable wicket-taker upfront.

name: Kyle Jamieson
analysis: Too tall for his own good? Struggles with injuries and his length can be easy pickings on slow, low tracks.

name: Daryl Mitchell
analysis: The Crisis Man. When the team is in trouble, he stands tall. Hits spin down the ground with immense power.

name: James Neesham
analysis: The freelancer! He can win you a match with a 15-ball cameo, but consistency is his biggest enemy.

name: Glenn Phillips
analysis: A live wire! He keeps, bowls spin, fields like a leopard, and bats like a beast. The ultimate utility player.

name: Rachin Ravindra
analysis: The Golden Boy! He plays spin beautifully (it's in the name!). A top-order batter who gives you 4 overs. Gold.

name: Tim Seifert
analysis: Cheeky shots galore! He loves the scoop and reverse sweep. Good backup keeper option against spin.

name: Ish Sodhi
analysis: Tall leggie who gets bounce. He can be expensive, but he always buys a wicket or two.

name: Paul Stirling
analysis: Stirlo is a legend! Hits the ball harder than anyone, but fitness and age are catching up. Still a threat in the powerplay.

name: Mark Adair
analysis: A genuine wicket-taker! He swings the new ball and whacks sixes at No. 8. A very valuable utility player.

name: Ross Adair
analysis: Paul's brother. Aggressive opener who goes "Bang-Bang" or back to the pavilion. A gamble for the brave.

name: Ben Calitz
analysis: Not a known commodity in top-tier international T20s yet. Better to skip.

name: Curtis Campher
analysis: The fighter! He took 4 wickets in 4 balls once. Scrappy with the bat and ball, always involved in the game.

name: Gareth Delany
analysis: Leg-spin all-rounder. Good fielder, hits long balls, but his bowling consistency is a bit of a lottery.

name: George Dockrell
analysis: Reinvented from spinner to finisher. Smart cricketer, but lacks the raw power of elite finishers.

name: Matthew Humphreys
analysis: Young left-arm spinner. A project player who could be handy on turners, but inexperienced.

name: Josh Little
analysis: IPL quality! Left-arm pace, hits the deck hard. He is Ireland's only true "Premium" T20 asset.

name: Barry McCarthy
analysis: Famous for that boundary save, but his bowling can be fodder for big hitters on small grounds.

name: Harry Tector
analysis: Pure Class. He plays spin beautifully and anchors the innings. A touch of elegance in a power-hitting world.

name: Tim Tector
analysis: Harry's younger brother. Still developing and not ready for the big stage yet.

name: Lorcan Tucker
analysis: Very busy player! Loves the scoop and reverse sweep. Keeps the scoreboard moving and annoys the bowlers.

name: Ben White
analysis: A leg-spinner useful in Asia, but often bowls too short. If he finds his length, he takes wickets.

name: Craig Young
analysis: A hit-the-deck bowler who gets bounce, but lacks variations. Good depth player, but not a starter.

name: Gerhard Erasmus
analysis: The Backbone! He bats, he bowls spin, he captains, and he fields with passion. If Namibia has a hope, it starts and ends with him. A must-have budget all-rounder.

name: Zane Green
analysis: A safe pair of hands behind the stumps, but with the bat, he is often stuck in first gear. In T20s, you need a Ferrari, not a tractor.

name: Bernard Scholtz
analysis: The Professor of Discipline! He bowls left-arm spin and barely gives an inch. On turning tracks, he is a nightmare for batters trying to slog.

name: Ruben Trumpelmann
analysis: The lefty who swings it! If there is moisture in the air or pitch, he becomes Mitchell Starc for the first 2 overs. A brilliant new-ball gamble.

name: JJ Smit
analysis: A hard-hitting finisher! Injuries have reduced his bowling, but if he connects with the bat, the ball stays hit. High impact, but fitness is a worry.

name: Jan Frylinck
analysis: The Fox! He doesn't have pace, but he has 50 variations of slower balls. On a slow, gripping wicket, he is very difficult to get away.

name: Louren Steenkamp
analysis: A domestic stalwart, but the jump to international quality is too high. He might struggle against express pace.

name: Malan Kruger
analysis: Solid technique, but "solid" doesn't win fantasy leagues. He lacks the explosive power game needed for this format.

name: Nicole Loftie-Eaton
analysis: The X-Factor! He holds the record for the fastest T20I century (33 balls!). He is inconsistent, but if he clicks, you win the league.

name: Jack Brassell
analysis: A young kid learning his trade. He has potential for the future, but throwing him into a mega auction now is too early.

name: Ben Shikongo
analysis: A backup seamer who runs in hard, but lacks the weapons to trouble top-tier international batters.

name: JC Balt
analysis: Very new to the scene. We haven't seen enough "dhamaka" to justify a bid. Pass.

name: Dylan Leicher
analysis: A developmental all-rounder. Keep an eye on him for the 2028 World Cup, but for now, save your virtual cash.

name: WP Myburgh
analysis: Likely a squad player who carries the drinks. You need points on the board, not hydration.

name: Max Heingo
analysis: Another backup option. Unless you are building a Namibia-only XI for a challenge, look elsewhere.

name: Shai Hope
analysis: Classy as a Rolls Royce, but sometimes you need a Ferrari in T20s. He plays beautiful drives, but "beauty" doesn't always equal "strike rate". Good anchor, but might slow you down.

name: Shimron Hetmyer
analysis: Hetty is pure dynamite! He hits spin into the orbit and celebrates with swag. But his fitness and form can fluctuate like the Sensex. High risk, massive reward.

name: Johnson Charles
analysis: Stand and Deliver! He doesn't move his feet, he just uses brute force. If it's in his arc, it's out of the park. If it swings, he‚Äôs in trouble.

name: Roston Chase
analysis: The "Fevicol" of the team. When the top order collapses (which happens often!), he sticks around. Plus, his off-spin is gold on turning tracks. Very smart utility pick.

name: Matthew Forde
analysis: A young gun with serious talent! He swings the new ball and can whack long sixes down the order. An underrated all-round package who flies under the radar.

name: Jason Holder
analysis: The Gentle Giant! Experienced, gets extra bounce because he's 9 feet tall, and hits long balls. A safe, reliable buy who gives you balance.

name: Akeal Hosein
analysis: The Sniper! He attacks the stumps in the powerplay with his arm-ball. Very disciplined, very economical. In subcontinent conditions, he is a must-have.

name: Shamar Joseph
analysis: The Hero of Gabba! He has pace, passion, and a broken toe story. Raw energy is high, but T20 experience is low. A wildcard entry!

name: Brandon King
analysis: Elegance personified. He sets the platform nicely. On a flat deck, he looks like a million dollars. Solid, reliable opener who doesn't throw his wicket away easily.

name: Gudakesh Motie
analysis: Chhupa Rustam Alert! This guy is a wicket-taking machine in the middle overs. Left-arm spin that turns and grips. Batters often underestimate him and pay the price!

name: Rovman Powell
analysis: Captain Power! He hits sixes that threaten the satellites. Spin or pace, it doesn't matter. A genuine match-winner who leads from the front.

name: Sherfane Rutherford
analysis: The Finisher! He has been in lethal form in leagues around the world. He waits for the death overs and then unleashes chaos. Great value buy.

name: Quentin Sampson
analysis: A mystery card! A hard-hitting all-rounder from Guyana who can surprise everyone. If you want a cheap "punt" that might turn into a jackpot, he's your man.

name: Jayden Seales
analysis: Young, fast, and skiddy. He is a serious talent in Test cricket, but still learning the dark arts of T20 death bowling. Buy for potential!

name: Romario Shepherd
analysis: The "Shepherd" who guides the ball to the boundary! Massive hitter at No. 7 or 8. His bowling can be expensive, but he picks up wickets with his variations.

name: Aiden Markram
analysis: Captain Cool! Classy batter who can anchor the ship and bowl handy off-spin. He is like Daal-Chawal‚Äîalways a good choice.

name: Corbin Bosch
analysis: A bits-and-pieces player who hasn't shown enough spark for the big stage yet. Keep scrolling.

name: Dewald Brevis
analysis: Baby AB! He plays shots that defy physics, but sometimes forgets to play the ones that defy getting out. Huge potential, huge risk.

name: Quinton de Kock
analysis: When QDK is in the mood, bowlers look for hiding spots. He loves Asian conditions and guarantees explosive starts.

name: Marco Jansen
analysis: The skyscraper! He gets bounce where there is none and hits sixes effortlessly. A complete T20 package you must have.

name: George Linde
analysis: A decent left-arm spinner, but in a pool full of superstars, he is just "okay." You want "wow," not "okay."

name: Keshav Maharaj
analysis: The silent assassin. He bowls in the powerplay, dries up runs, and frustrates batters into mistakes. Very smart buy.

name: Kwena Maphaka
analysis: The 17-year-old speedster! Fast, furious, and fearless. He is the X-factor rookie who could surprise everyone.

name: David Miller
analysis: Killer Miller! If it's in the arc, it's out of the park. Experienced finisher who knows how to win tight games.

name: Lungi Ngidi
analysis: He has good slower ones, but on a bad day, he leaks runs like a broken tap. Middle-overs gamble.

name: Anrich Nortje
analysis: Raw Speed! He bowls rockets, but sometimes rockets travel to the boundary very fast. Coming back from injuries, so handle with care.

name: Kagiso Rabada
analysis: Rabada ka Wada! Pace, precision, and passion. He is the leader of the pack and a guaranteed wicket-taker.

name: Ryan Rickelton
analysis: Have you seen his form in SA20? He is hitting everything! A brilliant budget option if you miss out on QDK.

name: Jason Smith
analysis: A fringe player. Unless you are his cousin, there is no strategic reason to bid for him here.

name: Tristan Stubbs
analysis: The young finisher! He hits long balls and keeps wickets. A rare commodity who is rapidly becoming a superstar. Buy him before he becomes unaffordable.

name: Rashid Khan
analysis: The MVP of the Universe. He doesn't just take wickets; he psychologically damages the opposition. Bat, bowl, field‚Äîhe does it all.

name: Noor Ahmad
analysis: The Sorcerer's Apprentice! Left-arm wrist spin is rarer than a diamond. Batters have no clue which way it's going.

name: Abdullah Ahmadzai
analysis: A standard seamer. In a team full of mystery spinners, he is just filling the numbers.

name: Sediqullah Atal
analysis: Young talent, but too raw for this level of competition. Let him cook in domestic cricket first.

name: Fazalhaq Farooqi
analysis: The Powerplay Destroyer! He swings it back into the right-handers and often kills the contest in the first 6 overs.

name: Rahmanullah Gurbaz
analysis: Fire and Ice (mostly fire). He attacks from ball one. A dangerous opener who can take the game away in minutes.

name: Naveen Ul Haq
analysis: The Master of Slower Balls. He has so many variations that even the batter gets confused. Clutch death bowler.

name: Mohammad Ishaq
analysis: A backup keeper without the batting credentials to demand a spot. Pass.

name: Shahidullah Kamal
analysis: A squad player. Doesn't have the impact to be in your fantasy XI.

name: Mohammad Nabi
analysis: The President! Vast experience, safe hands, and cool head. But age is catching up, and the strike rate is dipping.

name: Gulbadin Naib
analysis: The Muscle Man! He flexes his biceps and hits big shots. A "vibes" based player who can be a match-winner on his day.

name: Azmatullah Omarzai
analysis: A Gem! He swings the new ball and hits it miles with the bat. A proper, high-quality all-rounder who balances the side.

name: Mujeeb Ur Rahman
analysis: The Mystery is there, but so are the fitness issues. If he plays, he is dangerous. If he is injured, he is expensive bench strength.

name: Darwish Rasooli
analysis: Hasn't shown enough impact at the international level yet. Skip.

name: Ibrahim Zadran
analysis: The Anchor. Technically solid as a rock. He holds one end up while the others go "Bang Bang."

name: Suryakumar Yadav
analysis: He doesn't look at fielders, he looks for empty seats in the stands! If SKY is playing, the bowler is praying.

name: Abhishek Sharma
analysis: Explosive talent! He hits the ball hard, but sometimes forgets there are 20 overs, not just 2. A firecracker that can burst anywhere.

name: Tilak Varma
analysis: A touch of class in a chaotic format. He plays spin so late he can read the manufacturer's label on the ball. Perfect anchor.

name: Sanju Samson
analysis: Poetry in motion when he hits, a tragedy when he misses. He will win you one game single-handedly and break your heart in the next three.

name: Shivam Dube
analysis: The "Spin Destroyer"! Footwork? Who needs footwork when you have muscle? He stands tall and deposits spinners into the parking lot.

name: Ishan Kishan
analysis: Pocket Dynamo! He loves the ball coming onto the bat, but if the pitch is slow, he gets stuck like a car in traffic.

name: Hardik Pandya
analysis: Kung Fu Pandya! He walks with swagger and finishes with power. In the subcontinent, a seam-bowling all-rounder who hits spin is rarer than a unicorn.

name: Arshdeep Singh
analysis: The "Paaji" of death overs! He swings the new ball like a banana and lands yorkers on a coin. Stress-free buy.

name: Jasprit Bumrah
analysis: The Cheat Code. Even his "bad balls" take wickets. Buying him is like buying an insurance policy for your bowling attack‚Äîguaranteed returns!

name: Harshit Rana
analysis: Aggressive and in-your-face! He has the skills and the "flying kiss" send-off, but needs to make sure he doesn't leak runs in his anger.

name: Varun Chakravarthy
analysis: The Architect! His mystery is back, and on slow tracks, he is unplayable. If the pitch offers grip, he will run through the lineup like a hot knife through butter.

name: Kuldeep Yadav
analysis: The Magician! When the ball turns, batters dance to his tunes. He doesn't just take wickets; he embarrasses the opposition.

name: Axar Patel
analysis: Bapu is the ultimate 3D player‚Äîeconomical bowling, clutch batting, and rocket arm. He quietly wins you matches while others make the noise.

name: Washington Sundar
analysis: Tall, lanky, and stingy! He bowls in the powerplay like a miser refusing to lend money. Very high value on turning tracks.

name: Rinku Singh
analysis: Lord Rinku! The man has ice water in his veins. If you need 20 runs in the last over, he is the only guy who won't even blink.
